@node InstallMR " How to Install Mouse Reset "
@next WhatIsMR
 The recommmended way to install mouse reset is to drag it's icon into the
WBStartup directory of your System disk. Alternatively, it may be started
from the user-startup by inserting the following line:

	run <nil: >nil: MReset

You will also need to copy the program into your path if you use the second
method.
@endnode
@node WhatIsMR " What is Mouse Reset ? "
@next MRHist
 Mouse Reset is a simple program which provides a single window at the top of
the screen. The window is composed of a close gadget, depth gadget, non-
standard drag-bar and the reset button (To the left of the Depth Gadget).
 When the reset button is double-clicked, it will cause a soft reboot. RAD
disks will survive this.
 Mouse Reset is a commodity, but it doesn't have a hot key (Why would it?).
Starting the commodity a second time quits the program.
 The DragBar is very non-standard. This was due to the fact that I wanted to
place the reset button in the title Bar. The window "Sticks" to the
pointer, and stops when released.
 Also non-standard is the auto-close facility. If workbench is closed,
MReset will also close. When Workbench re-opens, so does MReset. It will take
account of any changes to screen mode, font size, etc when reopening (This
means that when you change a preference, you don't have to close MReset).

@endnode
@node MRHist " History of Mouse Reset "
@next DJKHist
Major Bugs found in most versions (during Go-Away,Come-Back cycles) before
version 7. Mouse Reset was written in assembler.

Mouse Reset 1.0                                 Size:1332
---------------
The original. Just responded immediately, rather than from double click

Mouse Reset 2.0                                 Size:1856
---------------
Double Click added. As this program is so simple, this was a major change.
Hence, the change from 1.0 to 2.0

Mouse Reset 3.0                                 Size:2088
---------------
Added custom gadget (bit awkward to use) and added go-away feature

Mouse Reset 3.5                                 Size:3420
---------------
Cleaned up version 3.0 . Really goes away well.

Version 3.6                                     Size:3604
-----------
Custom gadget larger. Now working on Version 4 (Commodity)

Version 4.0                                     Size:5960
-----------
Full Commodity compatability. Only supported method of killing. Took a while
to perfect.

Version 5.0                                     Size:5856
-----------
Moved Button. made it larger. Can now move button about. Planning something
very interesting.

Versions 5.1 & 5.2                              Size:5868 & 5888
------------------
Minor improvements. Put these programs to my tester, who found a major bug.

Version 6.0 (1st Release)                       Size:4560
-----------
Totally different program. Internally it is slightly cleaner, and all
of the routines have been re-written.(PS - turn WB onto 8 colours)

Version 7.0                                     Size:3840
-----------
Slightly cleaner still. Window drag changed. Still got a 8 colour button, if
you want it. I'm not sure myself where the 720 bytes went, because for some
reason, I have lost my source for Version 6. Hence, the decision to re-write
the program. Working on reducing size still further.

Version 7.05                                    Size:3788
------------
Minor re-working. Changed button from an image to a border. Hence will not
crash on machines with fast ram (Ooops! I only have chip ram). Also, 52 bytes
smaller. Ha Ha Ha.

Version 7.05                                    Size:3820
------------
I know, it is the same version number. Just changed the dragging routine
slightly, so as to make the window be on top during dragging. This was
preferable to losing the window behind large ones. Standards are made to be
broken, and this dragging operation is in no way "illegal". Still smaller
than version 6.0.

Version 7.1                                      Size:5332
-----------
Re-written a great deal. It is finally font and screen mode sensitive. It
will automatically close when Workbench does. It's lovely.
@endnode
